
@startuml

' Define classes
class Contract {
  +id: int
  +date: date
  +salesperson: Salesperson
  +airline: Airline
  +acquisitions: List<Acquisition>
}

class Acquisition {
  +id: int
  +contract: Contract
  +airplaneModel: String
  +price: double
  +options: List<String>
  +deliveryDate: date
}

class Salesperson {
  +id: int
  +name: String
  +contracts: List<Contract>
}

class Airline {
  +id: int
  +name: String
  +parentAirline: Airline
  +childAirlines: List<Airline>
}

class AirplaneModel {
  +id: int
  +modelName: String
  +description: String
}

' Associations
Contract "1" -- "0..*" Acquisition : has
Contract "1" -- "1" Salesperson : managed by
Contract "1" -- "1" Airline : associated with
Salesperson "1" -- "0..*" Contract : manages
Airline "1" -- "0..*" Airline : parent of (one-way)
Airline "1" -- "0..*" Airline : child of (one-way)

@enduml

---

### Explanation of Key Relationships:

- **`Contract`** contains multiple **`Acquisition`** entries.
- Each **`Contract`** is managed by a **`Salesperson`**, and a **`Salesperson`** can manage multiple contracts.
- Each **`Contract`** is associated with one **`Airline`**.
- **`Airline`** can have a **parent airline** and may have **child airlines**, representing hierarchical relationships.
- **`Acquisition`** includes details like airplane model, price, options, and delivery date.
- A **`AirplaneModel`** is a reusable entity that describes the type of aircraft being sold.

